@Light House Psychology  It's a shame too, as their core goal is wonderful (protecting women and children from violence isn't something I think anybody would or should contest), but tone deaf statements like that end up implying that men must always be somehow responsible. You know, the kind of people that others use to mock feminism but real feminists actually hate.

It's not even really a Metoo issue, either (at least not what metoo stands for). It's not unusual for movements and charities to focus on specific groups and doing that doesn't necessarily dismiss that others suffer too, it simply draws attention to specific examples that have impacted certain people. Things go to pot when you get people who are either so passionate about protecting one group that they turn on others/dismiss other possibilities, or people who falsely assume "this charity for this specific group has more attention, therefore its cause is more common."

People will always have bias from their own experiences, but that should never stop us from thinking critically.

